tool.name: Centrality

param.name: in_lines
param.dialogReference:
Input features in relation to which the centrality will be estimated.

These can be any spatial features. For supplementary contours generation, regular contour lines should be used.

param.name: cell_size
param.dialogReference: Cell size used for generation of centrality raster. It can be selected freely, without any dependency on the input raster DEM cell size. The smaller the cell size, the more precise the centrality estimation. However, extremely small values may cause long computation time. Set reasonably.

param.name: snap_raster
param.dialogReference: A raster used to snap the resulting centrality raster. Width and centrality rasters must be aligned and must have the same geometry. Therefore, if a width raster is computed first, then it should be used as snap raster in Centrality tool, and vice versa.

tool.summary:
This tool generates centrality raster.

A supplementary contour is generally informative if it is clearly not equidistant to contour lines that define the borders of its region. To estimate this property, we employ the notion of centrality. Centrality shows if the pixel is close to the middle position between contours (C = 1), close to one of the contours (C = 0) or is somewhere in between (0 < C < 1). Since a supplementary contour can be located anywhere within a region, an estimate of centrality is required for any point within a region. This is done by Centrality tool using a raster-based approach

Centrality is calculated using the following algorithm:

  1. Calculate Euclidean distance raster for regular contours (d1).

  2. Calculate Euclidean allocation raster for regular contours (this is a raster equivalent for Voronoy diagram).

  3. Vectorize Euclidean allocation raster and extract the boundaries between allocated zones.

  4. Rasterize regular contours using the same raster grid as Euclidean distance.

  5. Reclassify rasterized contours such that contour pixels are NULL and other pixels have the value of 1.

  6. Calculate Cost distance from allocation boundaries using the reclassified contours raster as a cost surface (dC). This disallows crossing regular contours during distance spreading.

  7. Calculate the resulting Centrality raster using the following map algebra expression: C = d1 / (d1 + dC)

NOTE: centrality is undefined for closed contours.

A detailed description of the method can be found in the following paper:

Samsonov T., Koshel S, Walther D., Jenny B. Automated placement of supplementary contour lines // International Journal of Geographical Information Science. — 2019. — Vol. 33. — DOI: 10.1080/13658816.2019.1610965
